==English==

===Etymology===
From {{prefix|up|date|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|noun}} {{enPR|ŭp'dāt}}, {{IPA|/ˈʌp.deɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{a|verb}} {{enPR|əp-dāt'|əp'dāt}}, {{IPA|/əpˈdeɪt/|/ˈʌp.deɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|En-us-update.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪt|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An advisement providing more up-to-date information than currently known.
#: {{ux|en|He gave me an '''update''' on the situation in New York.}}
# A change in information, a modification of existing or known data.
#: {{ux|en|I just made an '''update''' to the Wikipedia article on guerillas.}}
# An additional piece of information. An addition to existing information.
#: {{ux|en|I just made an '''update''' to my blog about my trip to Rome.}}
# A modification of something to a more recent, up-to-date version; (''in software'') a minor [[upgrade]].
#: {{ux|en|Our database receives an '''update''' every morning at 3 AM.}}
#: {{ux|en|I have a couple of '''updates''' to install on your laptop.}}
# A version of something which is newer than other versions.
#: {{ux|en|You should try the '''update''': it rocks.}}

====Usage notes====
In a software context there is a distinction between an {{m|en|update}} and an {{m|en|upgrade}}: ''updates''  usually include important security {{l|en|patch|patches|id=Q208218}} or bug fixes; an ''upgrade'' implies substantial new features and often has to be bought separately (in case of commercial software).

